    "lifecycle_state": "Author draft",
    "details": {
      "en": {
        "id": "en",
        "purpose": "To record and assess the bleeding risk in atrial fibrillation patients considered for anticoagulation.",
        "keywords": [
          "ORBIT Score",
          "bleeding risk",
          "anticoagulant",
          "anticoagulation",
          "atrial fibrillation"
        ],
        "use": "To be use when considering anticoagulation for patient with atrial fibrillation, by assessing the presence of the following variables (ORBIT):\n- O : Older age (1 point if age >74 years)\n- R : Reduced hemoglobin or hematocrit level (anaemia), hemoglobin (<13 mg/dL for males and <12 mg/dL for females) or hematocrit (<40% for males and <36% for females). Noted that different normal range apply for male and female gender (2 points if present)\n- B : Bleeding history (history of gastrointestinal bleeding, intracranial bleeding, or hemorrhagic stroke) (2 points if present)\n- I : Insufficient kidney function, based on the Glomerular Filtration Rate (GFR) (1 point if GFR < 60mL/min/1.73m2)\n- T: Treatment with antiplatelet agents (1 point if present)\n\nEvery point contributed by the variable will be summed into the ORBIT score. \n- Score 0-2 represents the low risk group with 2.4 events of bleed per 100 patient-years.\n- Score 3 represents the medium risk group with with 4.7 events of bleed per 100 patient-years.\n- Score 4-7 represents the high risk group with 8.1 events of bleed per 100 patient-years.\n\nPatient-years is the number of incident cases divided by the amount of person-time at risk.",
        "misuse": "ORBIT score does not take into account the choice of anticoagulant agents and the time in therapeutic range.",
        "copyright": "@CambioCDS"
      }
    },
    "other_details": {
      "references": "1. O'Brien EC, Simon DN, Thomas LE, et al. The ORBIT Bleeding Score: A Simple Bedside Score to Assess Bleeding Risk in Atrial Fibrillation. Eur Heart J. 2015;36(46):3258-64.\n\n2. O'Brien EC, Simon DN, Thomas LE, et al. The ORBIT Bleeding Score: A Simple Bedside Score to Assess Bleeding Risk in Atrial Fibrillation. Eur Heart J. 2015;36(46):3258-64."
    }
  },
